President Trump welcomed members of the Women's Suffrage Centennial Commission to the White House to celebrate the 100th anniversary of women securing the right to vote. He introduced and thanked the commission members for their work in telling the story of America's suffrage movement. He also announced that he would be signing a proclamation to commemorate the 100th anniversary of the 19th Amendment. Additionally, President Trump mentioned that he would be signing a full and complete pardon for Susan B. Anthony, who was never pardoned for her conviction for voting. The President also addressed other topics, including the upcoming House vote on the Postal Service bill, his response to Michelle Obama's speech at the Democratic National Convention, his views on suburban voters, and his support for democracy in Belarus. He also discussed his administration's efforts to lower drug prices and increase transparency in healthcare.